# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: force-directed-layout
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] While graph drawing can be a difficult problem, force-directed algorithms, being physical simulations, usually require no special knowledge about graph theory such as planarity.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed graph drawing algorithms assign forces among the set of edges and the set of nodes of a graph drawing.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Typically, spring-like attractive forces based on Hooke's law are used to attract pairs of endpoints of the graph's edges towards each other, while simultaneously repulsive forces like those of electrically charged particles based on Coulomb's law are used to separate all pairs of nodes.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] In equilibrium states for this system of forces, the edges tend to have uniform length (because of the spring forces), and nodes that are not connected by an edge tend to be drawn further apart (because of the electrical repulsion).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Edge attraction and vertex repulsion forces may be defined using functions that are not based on the physical behavior of springs and particles; for instance, some force-directed systems use springs whose attractive force is logarithmic rather than linear.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] An alternative model considers a spring-like force for every pair of nodes $(i,j)$ where the ideal length $\delta _{ij}$ of each spring is proportional to the graph-theoretic distance between nodes *i* and *j*, without using a separate repulsive force.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Minimizing the difference (usually the squared difference) between Euclidean and ideal distances between nodes is then equivalent to a metric multidimensional scaling problem.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] A force-directed graph can involve forces other than mechanical springs and electrical repulsion.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Analogues of magnetic fields may be used for directed graphs.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Repulsive forces may be placed on edges as well as on nodes in order to avoid overlap or near-overlap in the final drawing.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] In drawings with curved edges such as circular arcs or spline curves, forces may also be placed on the control points of these curves, for instance to improve their angular resolution.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Once the forces on the nodes and edges of a graph have been defined, the behavior of the entire graph under these sources may then be simulated as if it were a physical system.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] In such a simulation, the forces are applied to the nodes, pulling them closer together or pushing them further apart.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] This is repeated iteratively until the system comes to a mechanical equilibrium state; i.e., their relative positions do not change anymore from one iteration to the next.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] The positions of the nodes in this equilibrium are used to generate a drawing of the graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] For forces defined from springs whose ideal length is proportional to the graph-theoretic distance, stress majorization gives a very well-behaved (i.e., monotonically convergent) and mathematically elegant way to minimize these differences and, hence, find a good layout for the graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] It is also possible to employ mechanisms that search more directly for energy minima, either instead of or in conjunction with physical simulation.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Such mechanisms, which are examples of general global optimization methods, include simulated annealing and genetic algorithms.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] At least for graphs of medium size (up to 50–500 vertices), the results obtained have usually very good quality based on the following criteria: uniform edge length, uniform vertex distribution and showing symmetry.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] This last criterion is among the most important ones and is hard to achieve with any other type of algorithm.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed algorithms can be easily adapted and extended to fulfill additional aesthetic criteria.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] This makes them the most versatile class of graph drawing algorithms.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] cluster graph drawing, constrained graph drawing, and dynamic graph drawing.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Since they are based on physical analogies of common objects, like springs, the behavior of the algorithms is relatively easy to predict and understand.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Typical force-directed algorithms are simple and can be implemented in a few lines of code.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Other classes of graph-drawing algorithms, like the ones for orthogonal layouts, are usually much more involved.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Another advantage of this class of algorithm is the interactive aspect.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] By drawing the intermediate stages of the graph, the user can follow how the graph evolves, seeing it unfold from a tangled mess into a good-looking configuration.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] In some interactive graph drawing tools, the user can pull one or more nodes out of their equilibrium state and watch them migrate back into position.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] force-directed algorithms often appear in the literature and in practice (because they are relatively easy to understand), more reasoned approaches are starting to gain traction.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] problems - so extremely mature approaches exist.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] approach to metric MDS can be applied to graph drawing as described above.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Monotonic convergence, the property that the algorithm will at each iteration decrease the stress or cost of the layout, is important because it guarantees that the layout will eventually reach a local minimum and stop.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Damping schedules cause the algorithm to stop, but cannot guarantee that a true local minimum is reached.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] is the number of nodes of the input graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] ), and in every iteration, all pairs of nodes need to be visited and their mutual repulsive forces computed.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] However, since repulsive forces are local in nature the graph can be partitioned such that only neighboring vertices are considered.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed algorithms, when combined with a graph clustering approach, can draw graphs of millions of nodes.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] The local minimum found can be, in many cases, considerably worse than a global minimum, which translates into a low-quality drawing.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] moves of the vertices, the final result can be strongly influenced by the initial layout, that in most cases is randomly generated.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] The problem of poor local minima becomes more important as the number of vertices of the graph increases.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] A combined application of different algorithms is helpful to solve this problem.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] to improve the placement of neighbouring nodes.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Another technique to achieve a global minimum is to use a multilevel approach.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Because of the simple nature of the forces in this case, the system cannot get stuck in local minima, but rather converges to a unique global optimum configuration.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] Because of this work, embeddings of planar graphs with convex faces are sometimes called Tutte embeddings.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] The combination of attractive forces on adjacent vertices, and repulsive forces on all vertices, was first used by Eades (1984); additional pioneering work on this type of force-directed layout was done by Fruchterman & Reingold (1991).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-directed-graph-drawing] The idea of using only spring forces between all pairs of vertices, with ideal spring lengths equal to the vertices' graph-theoretic distance, is from Kamada & Kawai (1989).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In the context of chemistry, molecular physics, physical chemistry, and molecular modelling, a **force field** is a computational model that is used to describe the forces between atoms (or collections of atoms) within molecules or between molecules as well as in crystals.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are a variety of interatomic potentials.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] More precisely, the force field refers to the functional form and parameter sets used to calculate the potential energy of a system on the atomistic level.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Force fields are usually used in molecular dynamics or Monte Carlo simulations.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for a chosen energy function may be derived from classical laboratory experiment data, calculations in quantum mechanics, or both.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Force fields utilize the same concept as force fields in classical physics, with the main difference being that the force field parameters in chemistry describe the energy landscape on the atomistic level.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] From a force field, the acting forces on every particle are derived as a gradient of the potential energy with respect to the particle coordinates.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A large number of different force field types exist today (e.g. for organic molecules, ions, polymers, minerals, and metals).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Depending on the material, different functional forms are usually chosen for the force fields since different types of atomistic interactions dominate the material behavior.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] There are various criteria that can be used for categorizing force field parametrization strategies.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] An important differentiation is 'component-specific' and 'transferable'.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For a component-specific parametrization, the considered force field is developed solely for describing a single given substance (e.g. water).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For a transferable force field, all or some parameters are designed as building blocks and become transferable/ applicable for different substances (e.g. methyl groups in alkane transferable force fields).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] *Coarse-grained* potentials, which are often used in long-time simulations of macromolecules such as proteins, nucleic acids, and multi-component complexes, sacrifice chemical details for higher computing efficiency.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The bond and angle terms are usually modeled by quadratic energy functions that do not allow bond breaking.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A more realistic description of a covalent bond at higher stretching is provided by the more expensive Morse potential.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The functional form for dihedral energy is variable from one force field to another.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, "improper torsional" terms may be added to enforce the planarity of aromatic rings and other conjugated systems, and "cross-terms" that describe the coupling of different internal variables, such as angles and bond lengths.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Some force fields also include explicit terms for hydrogen bonds.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The nonbonded terms are computationally most intensive.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A popular choice is to limit interactions to pairwise energies.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The van der Waals term is usually computed with a Lennard-Jones potential or the Mie potential and the electrostatic term with Coulomb's law.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] However, both can be buffered or scaled by a constant factor to account for electronic polarizability.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields based on this or similar energy expressions have been proposed in the past decades for modeling different types of materials such as molecular substances, metals, glasses etc. - see below for a comprehensive list of force fields.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The term $l_{0,ij}$ is at times differently defined or taken at different thermodynamic conditions.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The bond stretching constant $k_{ij}$ can be determined from the experimental infrared spectrum, Raman spectrum, or high-level quantum-mechanical calculations.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The constant $k_{ij}$ determines vibrational frequencies in molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The stronger the bond is between atoms, the higher is the value of the force constant, and the higher the wavenumber (energy) in the IR/Raman spectrum.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Though the formula of Hooke's law provides a reasonable level of accuracy at bond lengths near the equilibrium distance, it is less accurate as one moves away.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In order to model the Morse curve better, one could employ cubic and higher powers.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] However, for most practical applications these differences are negligible, and inaccuracies in predictions of bond lengths are on the order of the thousandth of an angstrom, which is also the limit of reliability for common force fields.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A Morse potential can be employed instead to enable bond breaking and higher accuracy, even though it is less efficient to compute.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For reactive force fields, bond breaking and bond orders are additionally considered.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{angle}}$ is the force constant, $\theta _{i}$ the angle between three atoms and $\theta _{0}$ the equilibrium angle.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] where $k_{i}^{\text{dihedral}}$ is the force constant, $\phi _{i}$ the dihedral angle, $\delta _{i}$ the phase and n defines the number of minima or maxima between 0 and $2\pi$ .
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Dihedral terms admit a range of mathematical representations, as illustrated by the multiple dihedral functional forms provided in OpenMM’s standard forces.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Electrostatic interactions are represented by a Coulomb energy, which utilizes atomic charges $q_{i}$ to represent chemical bonding ranging from covalent to polar covalent and ionic bonding.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The typical formula is the Coulomb law: $E_{\text{Coulomb}}={\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {q_{i}q_{j}}{r_{ij}}},$ where $r_{ij}$ is the distance between two atoms i and j .
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The total Coulomb energy is a sum over all pairwise combinations of atoms and usually excludes 1, 2 bonded atoms, 1, 3 bonded atoms, as well as 1, 4 bonded atoms.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Atomic charges can make dominant contributions to the potential energy, especially for polar molecules and ionic compounds, and are critical to simulate the geometry, interaction energy, and the reactivity.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of charges usually uses some heuristic approach, with different possible solutions.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Historically the electrostatic potential (ESP) has been used to determine partial charges with the Merz-Kollman method being one of the first.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Other methods uses population based analysis schemes of wavefunctions like the Mulliken or Löwdin population analysis.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Another method to derive partial charges are charge equilibration methods like EEM, SQE or ACKS2.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The idea is to assign geometry-dependent charges by letting electronegativity differences drive charge flow between atoms until a self-consistent minimum of the electrostatic energy is reached.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Atomistic interactions in crystal systems significantly deviate from those in molecular systems, e.g. of organic molecules.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems, particularly multi-body interactions, these interactions are important and cannot be neglected if a high accuracy of the force field is the aim.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For crystal systems with covalent bonding, bond order potentials are usually used, e.g.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For metal systems, usually embedded atom potentials are used.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Additionally, Drude model potentials have been developed, which describe a form of attachment of electrons to nuclei.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In addition to the functional form of the potentials, a force fields consists of the parameters of these functions.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Together, they specify the interactions on the atomistic level.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The parametrization, i.e. determining of the parameter values, is crucial for the accuracy and reliability of the force field.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Different parametrization procedures have been developed for the parametrization of different substances, e.g. metals, ions, and molecules.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For different material types, usually different parametrization strategies are used.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In general, two main types can be distinguished for the parametrization, either using data/ information from the atomistic level, e.g. from quantum mechanical calculations or spectroscopic data, or using data from macroscopic properties, e.g. the hardness or compressibility of a given material.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Often a combination of these routes is used.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Hence, one way or the other, the force field parameters are always determined in an empirical way.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Nevertheless, the term 'empirical' is often used in the context of force field parameters when macroscopic material property data was used for the fitting.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Experimental data (microscopic and macroscopic) included for the fit, for example, the enthalpy of vaporization, enthalpy of sublimation, dipole moments, and various spectroscopic properties such as vibrational frequencies.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Often, for molecular systems, quantum mechanical calculations in the gas phase are used for parametrizing intramolecular interactions and parametrizing intermolecular dispersive interactions by using macroscopic properties such as liquid densities.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The assignment of atomic charges often follows quantum mechanical protocols with some heuristics, which can lead to significant deviation in representing specific properties.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A large number of workflows and parametrization procedures have been employed in the past decades using different data and optimization strategies for determining the force field parameters.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] They differ significantly, which is also due to different focuses of different developments.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The parameters for molecular simulations of biological macromolecules such as proteins, DNA, and RNA were often derived/transferred from observations for small organic molecules, which are more accessible for experimental studies and quantum calculations.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Atom types are defined for different elements as well as for the same elements in sufficiently different chemical environments.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For example, oxygen atoms in water and an oxygen atoms in a carbonyl functional group are classified as different force field types.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Typical molecular force field parameter sets include values for atomic mass, atomic charge, Lennard-Jones parameters for every atom type, as well as equilibrium values of bond lengths, bond angles, and dihedral angles.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The bonded terms refer to pairs, triplets, and quadruplets of bonded atoms, and include values for the effective spring constant for each potential.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Efforts to provide open source codes and methods include openMM and openMD.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The use of semi-automation or full automation, without input from chemical knowledge, is likely to increase inconsistencies at the level of atomic charges, for the assignment of remaining parameters, and likely to dilute the interpretability and performance of parameters.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A open-source software to derive parameters for different potential function is the Alexandria Chemistry Toolkit (ACT) which was published in 2025.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] It can generate and optimize physics-based force fields from scratch by machine learning.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Atom and bond parameters are considered genes of a genome, where force field accuracy is tied to the fitness of the genome.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Using a genetic algorithm (GA) and a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm, it can perform chromosomal crossovers and induce point mutations for global and local improvements closely resembling actual evolutionary operators.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Force field parameters are trained on quantum chemical energies, such as Symmetry-Adapted perturbation theory (SAPT) for non-covalent dimer interaction energies and Second-Order Møller-Plesset Perturbation Theory (MP2) scans for intramolecular energies.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A large number of force fields has been published in the past decades - mostly in scientific publications.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In recent years, some databases have attempted to collect, categorize and make force fields digitally available.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Therein, different databases focus on different types of force fields.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For example, the openKim database focuses on interatomic functions describing the individual interactions between specific elements.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The TraPPE database focuses on transferable force fields of organic molecules (developed by the Siepmann group).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The MolMod database focuses on molecular and ionic force fields (both component-specific and transferable).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Functional forms and parameter sets have been defined by the developers of interatomic potentials and feature variable degrees of self-consistency and transferability.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] When functional forms of the potential terms vary or are mixed, the parameters from one interatomic potential function can typically not be used together with another interatomic potential function.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In some cases, modifications can be made with minor effort, for example, between 9-6 Lennard-Jones potentials to 12-6 Lennard-Jones potentials.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Transfers from Buckingham potentials to harmonic potentials, or from Embedded Atom Models to harmonic potentials, on the contrary, would require many additional assumptions and may not be possible.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] In many cases, force fields can be straight forwardly combined.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Yet, often, additional specifications and assumptions are required.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] All interatomic potentials are based on approximations and experimental data, therefore often termed *empirical*.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The performance varies from higher accuracy than density functional theory (DFT) calculations, with access to million times larger systems and time scales, to random guesses depending on the force field.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The use of accurate representations of chemical bonding, combined with reproducible experimental data and validation, can lead to lasting interatomic potentials of high quality with much fewer parameters and assumptions in comparison to DFT-level quantum methods.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Possible limitations include atomic charges, also called point charges.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Most force fields rely on point charges to reproduce the electrostatic potential around molecules, which works less well for anisotropic charge distributions.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Electronic polarization of the environment may be better included by using *polarizable force fields* or using a macroscopic dielectric constant.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] However, application of one value of dielectric constant is a coarse approximation in the highly heterogeneous environments of proteins, biological membranes, minerals, or electrolytes.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] All types of van der Waals forces are also strongly environment-dependent because these forces originate from interactions of induced and "instantaneous" dipoles (see Intermolecular force).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The original Fritz London theory of these forces applies only in a vacuum.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A more general theory of van der Waals forces in condensed media was developed by A.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] McLachlan in 1963 and included the original London's approach as a special case.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The McLachlan theory predicts that van der Waals attractions in media are weaker than in vacuum and follow the *like dissolves like* rule, which means that different types of atoms interact more weakly than identical types of atoms.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] This is in contrast to *combinatorial rules* or Slater-Kirkwood equation applied for development of the classical force fields.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The *combinatorial rules* state that the interaction energy of two dissimilar atoms (e.g., C...N) is an average of the interaction energies of corresponding identical atom pairs (i.e., C...C and N...N).
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] According to McLachlan's theory, the interactions of particles in media can even be fully repulsive, as observed for liquid helium, however, the lack of vaporization and presence of a freezing point contradicts a theory of purely repulsive interactions.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Measurements of attractive forces between different materials (Hamaker constant) have been explained by Jacob Israelachvili.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] For example, "*the interaction between hydrocarbons across water is about 10% of that across vacuum*".
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Such effects are represented in molecular dynamics through pairwise interactions that are spatially more dense in the condensed phase relative to the gas phase and reproduced once the parameters for all phases are validated to reproduce chemical bonding, density, and cohesive/surface energy.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Limitations have been strongly felt in protein structure refinement.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The major underlying challenge is the huge conformation space of polymeric molecules, which grows beyond current computational feasibility when containing more than ~20 monomers.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Participants in Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) did not try to refine their models to avoid "*a central embarrassment of molecular mechanics, namely that energy minimization or molecular dynamics generally leads to a model that is less like the experimental structure*".
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Force fields have been applied successfully for protein structure refinement in different X-ray crystallography and NMR spectroscopy applications, especially using program XPLOR.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] However, the refinement is driven mainly by a set of experimental constraints and the interatomic potentials serve mainly to remove interatomic hindrances.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The results of calculations were practically the same with rigid sphere potentials implemented in program DYANA (calculations from NMR data), or with programs for crystallographic refinement that use no energy functions at all.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] These shortcomings are related to interatomic potentials and to the inability to sample the conformation space of large molecules effectively.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Thereby also the development of parameters to tackle such large-scale problems requires new approaches.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] A specific problem area is homology modeling of proteins.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Meanwhile, alternative empirical scoring functions have been developed for ligand docking, protein folding, homology model refinement, computational protein design, and modeling of proteins in membranes.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] It was also argued that some protein force fields operate with energies that are irrelevant to protein folding or ligand binding.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The parameters of proteins force fields reproduce the enthalpy of sublimation, i.e., energy of evaporation of molecular crystals.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] However, protein folding and ligand binding are thermodynamically closer to crystallization, or liquid-solid transitions as these processes represent *freezing* of mobile molecules in condensed media.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Thus, free energy changes during protein folding or ligand binding are expected to represent a combination of an energy similar to heat of fusion (energy absorbed during melting of molecular crystals), a conformational entropy contribution, and solvation free energy.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The heat of fusion is significantly smaller than enthalpy of sublimation.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Hence, the potentials describing protein folding or ligand binding need more consistent parameterization protocols, e.g., as described for IFF.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The depths of modified Lennard-Jones potentials derived from protein engineering data were also smaller than in typical potential parameters and followed the *like dissolves like* rule, as predicted by McLachlan theory.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Several force fields explicitly capture polarizability, where a particle's effective charge can be influenced by electrostatic interactions with its neighbors.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Core-shell models are common, which consist of a positively charged core particle, representing the polarizable atom, and a negatively charged particle attached to the core atom through a spring-like harmonic oscillator potential.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Recent examples include polarizable models with virtual electrons that reproduce image charges in metals and polarizable biomolecular force fields.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] The set of parameters used to model water or aqueous solutions (basically a force field for water) is called a water model.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Many water models have been proposed; some examples are TIP3P, TIP4P, SPC, flexible simple point charge water model (flexible SPC), ST2, and mW.
[src:force-directed-layout/force-field-chemistry] Other solvents and methods of solvent representation are also applied within computational chemistry and physics; these are termed solvent models.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] A drawing of a graph or **network diagram** is a pictorial representation of the vertices and edges of a graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] This drawing should not be confused with the graph itself: very different layouts can correspond to the same graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] In the abstract, all that matters is which pairs of vertices are connected by edges.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] In the concrete, however, the arrangement of these vertices and edges within a drawing affects its understandability, usability, fabrication cost, and aesthetics.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] The problem gets worse if the graph changes over time by adding and deleting edges (dynamic graph drawing) and the goal is to preserve the user's mental map.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] Graphs are frequently drawn as node–link diagrams in which the vertices are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] Node–link diagrams can be traced back to the 14th-16th century works of Pseudo-Lull which were published under the name of Ramon Llull, a 13th century polymath.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] Pseudo-Lull drew diagrams of this type for complete graphs in order to analyze all pairwise combinations among sets of metaphysical concepts.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] In the case of directed graphs, arrowheads form a commonly used graphical convention to show their orientation; however, user studies have shown that other conventions such as tapering provide this information more effectively.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] Upward planar drawing uses the convention that every edge is oriented from a lower vertex to a higher vertex, making arrowheads unnecessary.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] Many different quality measures have been defined for graph drawings, in an attempt to find objective means of evaluating their aesthetics and usability.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] In addition to guiding the choice between different layout methods for the same graph, some layout methods attempt to directly optimize these measures.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] In addition, the placement and routing steps of electronic design automation (EDA) are similar in many ways to graph drawing, as is the problem of greedy embedding in distributed computing, and the graph drawing literature includes several results borrowed from the EDA literature.
[src:force-directed-layout/graph-drawing] There are many algorithms for graph drawing.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] The ideal form for a layered drawing would be an upward planar drawing, in which all edges are oriented in a consistent direction and no pairs of edges cross.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] In its simplest form, layered graph drawing algorithms may require O(*mn*) time in graphs with *n* vertices and *m* edges, because of the large number of dummy vertices that may be created.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] However, for some variants of the algorithm, it is possible to simulate the effect of the dummy vertices without actually constructing them explicitly, leading to a near-linear time implementation.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] The "dot" tool in Graphviz produces layered drawings.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] A layered graph drawing algorithm is also included in Microsoft Automatic Graph Layout and in Tulip.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] Although typically drawn with vertices in rows and edges proceeding from top to bottom, layered graph drawing algorithms may instead be drawn with vertices in columns and edges proceeding from left to right.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] The same algorithmic framework has also been applied to radial layouts in which the graphs are arranged in concentric circles around some starting node and to three-dimensional layered drawings of graphs.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] In layered graph drawings with many long edges, edge clutter may be reduced by grouping sets of edges into bundles and routing them together through the same set of dummy vertices.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] Similarly, for drawings with many edges crossing between pairs of consecutive layers, the edges in maximal bipartite subgraphs may be grouped into confluent bundles.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] Drawings in which the vertices are arranged in layers may be constructed by algorithms that do not follow Sugiyama's framework.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] For instance, it is possible to tell whether an undirected graph has a drawing with at most *k* crossings, using *h* layers, in an amount of time that is polynomial for any fixed choice of *k* and *h*, using the fact that the graphs that have drawings of this type have bounded pathwidth.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] For layered drawings of concept lattices, a hybrid approach combining Sugiyama's framework with additive methods (in which each vertex represents a set and the position of the vertex is a sum of vectors representing elements in the set) may be used.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] In this hybrid approach, the vertex permutation and coordinate assignment phases of the algorithm are replaced by a single phase in which the horizontal position of each vertex is chosen as a sum of scalars representing the elements for that vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/layered-graph-drawing] Layered graph drawing methods have also been used to provide an initial placement for force-directed graph drawing algorithms.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **tree** is an undirected graph in which every pair of distinct vertices is connected by *exactly one* path, or equivalently, a connected acyclic undirected graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A **forest** is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by *at most one* path, or equivalently an acyclic undirected graph, or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A directed tree, oriented tree, polytree, or singly connected network is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A polyforest (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The various kinds of data structures referred to as trees in computer science have underlying graphs that are trees in graph theory, although such data structures are generally rooted trees.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree may be directed, called a directed rooted tree, either making all its edges point away from the root—in which case it is called an arborescence or out-tree—or making all its edges point towards the root—in which case it is called an anti-arborescence or in-tree.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree itself has been defined by some authors as a directed graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A rooted forest is a disjoint union of rooted trees.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The term *tree* was coined in 1857 by the British mathematician Arthur Cayley.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] It may, however, be considered as a forest consisting of zero trees.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* (or inner vertex) is a vertex of degree at least 2.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Similarly, an *external vertex* (or outer vertex, terminal vertex or leaf) is a vertex of degree 1.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A branch vertex in a tree is a vertex of degree at least 3.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] An *irreducible tree* (or series-reduced tree) is a tree in which there is no vertex of degree 2 (enumerated at sequence A000014 in the OEIS).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *forest* is an undirected acyclic graph or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Trivially so, each connected component of a forest is a tree.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] As special cases, the order-zero graph (a forest consisting of zero trees), a single tree, and an edgeless graph, are examples of forests.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Since for every tree *V* − *E* = 1, we can easily count the number of trees that are within a forest by subtracting the difference between total vertices and total edges.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] *V* − *E* = number of trees in a forest.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *polytree* (or *directed tree* or *oriented tree* or *singly connected network*) is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is both connected and acyclic.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Some authors restrict the phrase "directed tree" to the case where the edges are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see arborescence).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *polyforest* (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is acyclic.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] As with directed trees, some authors restrict the phrase "directed forest" to the case where the edges of each connected component are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see branching).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *rooted tree* is a tree in which one vertex has been designated the root.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The edges of a rooted tree can be assigned a natural orientation, either away from or towards the root, in which case the structure becomes a directed rooted tree.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] When a directed rooted tree has an orientation away from the root, it is called an *arborescence* or *out-tree*; when it has an orientation towards the root, it is called an *anti-arborescence* or *in-tree*.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The tree-order is the partial ordering on the vertices of a tree with *u* < *v* only if the unique path from the root to v passes through u.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree T that is a subgraph of some graph G is a normal tree if the ends of every T-path in G are comparable in this tree-order (Diestel 2005, p.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Rooted trees, often with an additional structure such as an ordering of the neighbors at each vertex, are a key data structure in computer science; see tree data structure.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] In a context where trees typically have a root, a tree without any designated root is called a *free tree*.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *labeled tree* is a tree in which each vertex is given a unique label.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The vertices of a labeled tree on n vertices (for nonnegative integers n) are typically given the labels 1, 2, …, *n*.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *recursive tree* is a labeled rooted tree where the vertex labels respect the tree order (i.e., if *u* < *v* for two vertices u and v, then the label of u is smaller than the label of v).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] In a rooted tree, the **parent** of a vertex v is the vertex connected to v on the path to the root; every vertex has a unique parent, except the root has no parent.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *child* of a vertex v is a vertex of which v is the parent.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] An *ascendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either the parent of v or is (recursively) an ascendant of a parent of v.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *descendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either a child of v or is (recursively) a descendant of a child of v.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *sibling* to a vertex v is any other vertex on the tree that shares a parent with v.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* is a vertex that is not a leaf.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of a vertex in a rooted tree is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of the tree is the height of the root.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The *depth* of a vertex is the length of the path to its root (*root path*).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The depth of a tree is the maximum depth of any vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Depth is commonly needed in the manipulation of the various self-balancing trees, AVL trees in particular.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] The root has depth zero, leaves have height zero, and a tree with only a single vertex (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Conventionally, an empty tree (a tree with no vertices, if such are allowed) has depth and height −1.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A *k-ary tree* (for nonnegative integers k) is a rooted tree in which each vertex has at most k children.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] 2-ary trees are often called *binary trees*, while 3-ary trees are sometimes called *ternary trees*.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] An *ordered tree* (alternatively, *plane tree* or *positional tree*) is a rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] This is called a "plane tree" because an ordering of the children is equivalent to an embedding of the tree in the plane, with the root at the top and the children of each vertex lower than that vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Given an embedding of a rooted tree in the plane, if one fixes a direction of children, say left to right, then an embedding gives an ordering of the children.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Conversely, given an ordered tree, and conventionally drawing the root at the top, then the child vertices in an ordered tree can be drawn left-to-right, yielding an essentially unique planar embedding.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Cayley's formula states that there are *n**n*−2 trees on n labeled vertices.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] A more general problem is to count spanning trees in an undirected graph, which is addressed by the matrix tree theorem.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] (Cayley's formula is the special case of spanning trees in a complete graph.) The similar problem of counting all the subtrees regardless of size is #P-complete in the general case (Jerrum (1994)).
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] Counting the number of unlabeled free trees is a harder problem.
[src:force-directed-layout/tree-graph-theory] No closed formula for the number *t*(*n*) of trees with n vertices up to graph isomorphism is known.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] In a diagram of a graph, a vertex is usually represented by a circle with a label, and an edge is represented by a line or arrow extending from one vertex to another.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] The two vertices forming an edge are said to be the endpoints of this edge, and the edge is said to be incident to the vertices.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A vertex *w* is said to be adjacent to another vertex *v* if the graph contains an edge (*v*,*w*).
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] The neighborhood of a vertex *v* is an induced subgraph of the graph, formed by all vertices adjacent to *v*.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] The degree of a vertex, denoted 𝛿(v) in a graph is the number of edges incident to it.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] An **isolated vertex** is a vertex with degree zero; that is, a vertex that is not an endpoint of any edge (the example image illustrates one isolated vertex).
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A **leaf vertex** (also **pendant vertex**) is a vertex with degree one.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] In a directed graph, one can distinguish the outdegree (number of outgoing edges), denoted 𝛿 +(v), from the indegree (number of incoming edges), denoted 𝛿−(v); a **source vertex** is a vertex with indegree zero, while a **sink vertex** is a vertex with outdegree zero.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A simplicial vertex is one whose closed neighborhood forms a clique: every two neighbors are adjacent.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A universal vertex is a vertex that is adjacent to every other vertex in the graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A cut vertex is a vertex the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph; a vertex separator is a collection of vertices the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph into small pieces.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A k-vertex-connected graph is a graph in which removing fewer than *k* vertices always leaves the remaining graph connected.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] An independent set is a set of vertices no two of which are adjacent, and a vertex cover is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of each edge in the graph.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex space of a graph is a vector space having a set of basis vectors corresponding with the graph's vertices.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A graph is vertex-transitive if it has symmetries that map any vertex to any other vertex.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] In the context of graph enumeration and graph isomorphism it is important to distinguish between **labeled vertices** and **unlabeled vertices**.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] A labeled vertex is a vertex that is associated with extra information that enables it to be distinguished from other labeled vertices; two graphs can be considered isomorphic only if the correspondence between their vertices pairs up vertices with equal labels.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] An unlabeled vertex is one that can be substituted for any other vertex based only on its adjacencies in the graph and not based on any additional information.
[src:force-directed-layout/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex figure of a vertex in a polyhedron is analogous to the neighborhood of a vertex in a graph.
